Title: A Day of Fallen Night (The Roots of Chaos, #0)
Author: Samantha    Shannon
My Review:
5 stars are not enough!!! one silly spoiler below the line but samantha shannon's way with words is absolutely breathtaking. if you haven't read this or priory, what are you doing. seriously start now. absolutely immersive fantasy and love stories. hot take but this is what the standard for the genre of romantasy be-- characters can have a love story that is developed and beautiful (and is maybe the best description of love I've ever read I seriously dogeared so many pages) but not the central plot point. also the cover art?? is spectacular but pales in comparison to the descriptions within. this is one of those books where you can see everything happening. dont talk to me for the next week unless you want to talk about this book. definitely read priory first because that had all the dragon descriptions.


this book has everything:
conjuring invented animals with a single sentence? "they resembled mongooses in the way a lion resembles a cat" ✅
depictions of love and loss to seriously tug at your heart? "she had locked it all into a box in her mind. there were fingerprints on its lid, from the nights when she had woken alone, and the days she had spent trying not to look back" ✅
enough food descriptions to make you think you're reading a grrm book? ✅
-----------
big win for women that in a Very Gay book, the one boy with gay male parents can't figure out he is bi? ✅

Title: Black Man in a White Coat: A Doctor's Reflections on Race and Medicine
Author: Damon Tweedy
My Review: 3.5 for me -- I was very interested in the topic and the author's perspective but I think it got weaker the more I read. I wanted more about his journey personally (why did he choose psychiatry? what is it like being a married doctor pair?) which disappeared after his early chapters. but okay, everyone gets their own style of memoir. what bothered me more was that his ultimate thesis is that you can get over prejudice by interacting with people or living their experiences, which feels very narrow minded to me -- it doesn't require any introspection about our own biases and puts the onus on groups to show that they are different than stereotypes. I would highly recommend the first half of this book, and once you get to the comment about being nice to nurses just so that they don't make your life hard you can kinda skim from there.

Title: Yellowface
Author: R.F. Kuang
My Review:
I devoured it in one sitting but there is clearly so much depth I want to do another read to catch more!!! as others have said I would read a shopping list if rfk wrote it but this is genuinely worth your time. the babel reference was a treat ✨

more thoughts-- yes the characters were semi caricatures but I think that was the point of the satire because they were easy footholds to move the story along and provide food for thought without having to spend narrative space explaining a human who is plucked right from our present time line. all are espousing correct and incorrect and morally gray ideas in a way that is not unbelievable at ALL and forces the reader to contend with where they have situated themselves in all too common occurrences in book twitter wars. I think this is 4d chess where there are layers that I know I don't get and layers I think an uncritical reader will miss entirely and the book remains valuable at any level as long as you dont get to the end without realizing it's a satire (which would only be possible for the densest of readers who are themselves characters in the book)

wild: this was the first one where i was really invested along with the characters and i was eyes bulging when she said the thing about the kid!!! i enjoy the characters being complicated and you dont know who to root for completely and the girl hiding her ecstasy was a funny line
light: CRUSHED me im so sad for that girl, this one was the one that haunted me the longest
second chances: i liked this one and the rumination of a world turned so quickly upside down and not knowing like what to focus on or who to talk with but i could have used a few more pages!! she was gone at the end but where!! i also read the first scene in the mattress store thinking she was a ghost or something the first time so i had to retrace that part
windfalls: PAIN i had to put the book down for a bit after this one, the storytelling was so vivid
who willl greet you at home: i feel like i got the point of this one but not quite? wanted a bit more world building to understand the dolls but this was a good first turn into the science fiction
buchi’s girls: i was rooting so hard for the chicken
WIMWAMFFTS: i loved the idea of this one and read it twice bc i quite enjoyed it but i struggled the first time because i was focusing so much on the invented geopolitical conflict which ended up being not very relevant? / it was meaningful but i think deserved its own story to flourish because it was a good idea. this one def i could see being transformed into full length novel i really enjoyed how clever the premise was and how quickly she could build up a world, have you understand it, and then have some parts of it torn down by the end and have feelings about it !!
glory: really enjoyed!!! i feel like this is something a lot of authors strive to and can’t get right with short stories of having a conflicted decision / cliff hanger at the end whos resolution doesn’t change the main drive of the story, and i felt for her so much with the dog mouth thing holy cow
WIAV: i liked it fine enough but it didn't totally move me, i thought that ant was going to give the stone to the girl and it would be river's daughter since he forgot where she is
redemption: dhskjlhajk more pain if i was the editor i would have swapped this and glory in order because it was such a morose story but i guess the last line was supposed to be hopeful

// im going to write a full review SOON but WOW add this to your to-read please and thank you!! ty sofea

Title: Superior: The Return of Race Science
Author: Angela Saini
My Review:
this is a good and important book, which I don't want to downplay, and I will be recommending it to my mother a geneticist (hi mom). however, I think a lot of the arguments the author made are more nuanced than presented, and a lot of the reason I felt like I was supposed to agree with their POV was because of how evil the racists are -- this is true (and another reason I didn't love the book was how much time was spent on 'here is everything about an evil man') but doesn't really strengthen the argument as to why we should never do certain types of research. I don't have to agree with an author to like their book but in this case I didn't feel like they were doing anything to persuade me to their side, and these are really interesting and important debates I do want to hear more educated opinions on which is why it let me down a bit. really excited to talk about these topics with our reading group exactly because I want more of the gray areas and to flesh things out more.

* actually downgrading my 4 star to 3 star simply because in all of the research done, "intelligence" and "IQ" were taken as real things and NONE of the issues with them were even mentioned, which was a HUGE miss especially for a book on the problems of race science.

Title: Lean Semesters: How Higher Education Reproduces Inequity (Critical University Studies)
Author: Sekile M. Nzinga
My Review: ok so this turned out to be more of a long scientific article than it did a book, both in organizational structure and language, but I found it a really powerful read once I put myself into the more academic mindset! glad I finally was able to get a copy to read. put into stark contrast the differences between people getting funded "tuition free" phds (like mine) and those paying for their own research + school + living while pursuing them. and, I learned a lot about the adjunct faculty job market I did not know. made me reconsider a mental frame of higher education leading to a linear improvement in social+economic possibilities for all. definitely want to read more in this area of research, because parts of the nuances about the ways neoliberalism has affected academic dynamics definitely went over my head.
